        scoreYou:
          'There are four ways to score for this mission:\n1: Score 4 VP if 1 or more enemy units that started the turn within range of an objective are destroyed. [Any battle round, end of your turn]\n2: Score 4 VP if only one operation marker is on the battlefield and you have one or more friendly units within that terrain area and there are no enemy units within that terrain area. [Any battle round, end of your turn]\nEach player can sensor sweep once per turn which allows them to remove an operation marker. Sensor sweep is an action that you can do when a friendly unit is within range of a central objective and completes at the end of your turn if you control that objective. Both players can do this, identically. For the sake of brevity, the remaining operation marker will be called “the relic”.\n3: Score 4 VP if you control 1 or more objectives, excluding home. [2nd battle round onwards, end of your command phase, changes to end of your turn in battle round 5]\n4: Score 5 VP at end of battle if you control the relic and no enemy units are within it. [End of battle]\nYeah, so this one’s kind of a shitshow. Let’s look at idealized scoring without kill points:\n• Turn 1 - 0 VP\n• Turn 2 - 4 VP (from holding 1 objective)\n• Turn 3 - 8 VP (holding 1, holding the relic)\n• Turn 4 - 8 VP\n• Turn 5 - 13 VP (holding 1, scoring the relic, holding the relic at end of battle)\nThat’s 33 VP, meaning that you only need to score 12 VP from the kill points objective to max out primary. But here’s the thing: it might not look like this at all. The PA player wants to do actions because it will get them VP. And you want to be able to dictate where the relic ends up, so you have to be judicious as to whether or not you’re going to interact with this process at all . Some of the TTB brain trust think that the disruption player should just ignore that part of the mission completely and focus on other ways to score and secondaries. Others think that you have to time it right by trying to perform the 2nd sensor sweep to try to choose the right spot for the relic. I’m not sure which way is better, and it’s going to take repetition for people to figure it out.',
